# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sonet-sdh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] An optical communication system uses a transmitter, which encodes a message into an optical signal, a channel, which carries the signal to its destination, and a receiver, which reproduces the message from the received optical signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] When electronic equipment is not employed the 'receiver' is a person visually observing and interpreting a signal, which may be either simple (such as the presence of a beacon fire) or complex (such as lights using color codes or flashed in a Morse code sequence).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Modern communication relies on optical networking systems using optical fiber, optical amplifiers, lasers, switches, routers, and other related technologies.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Free-space optical communication use lasers to transmit signals in space, while terrestrial forms are naturally limited by geography and weather.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] This article provides a basic introduction to different forms of optical communication.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Visual techniques such as smoke signals, beacon fires, hydraulic telegraphs, ship flags and semaphore lines were the earliest forms of optical communication.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Hydraulic telegraph semaphores date back to the 4th century BCE Greece.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Distress flares are still used by mariners in emergencies, while lighthouses and navigation lights are used to communicate navigation hazards.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The heliograph uses a mirror to reflect sunlight to a distant observer.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] When a signaler tilts the mirror to reflect sunlight, the distant observer sees flashes of light that can be used to transmit a prearranged signaling code.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Naval ships often use signal lamps and Morse code in a similar way.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Aircraft pilots often use visual approach slope indicator (VASI) projected light systems to land safely, especially at night.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Military aircraft landing on an aircraft carrier use a similar system to land correctly on a carrier deck.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The coloured light system communicates the aircraft's height relative to a standard landing glideslope.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] As well, airport control towers still use Aldis lamps to transmit instructions to aircraft whose radios have failed.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] A 'semaphore telegraph', also called a 'semaphore line', 'optical telegraph', 'shutter telegraph chain', 'Chappe telegraph', or 'Napoleonic semaphore', is a system used for conveying information by means of visual signals, using towers with pivoting arms or shutters, also known as blades or paddles.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the mechanical elements; it is read when the shutter is in a fixed position.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Semaphore lines were a precursor of the electrical telegraph.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] They were far faster than post riders for conveying a message over long distances, but far more expensive and less private than the electrical telegraph lines which would later replace them.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The maximum distance that a pair of semaphore telegraph stations can bridge is limited by geography, weather and the availability of light; thus, in practical use, most optical telegraphs used lines of relay stations to bridge longer distances.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Each relay station would also require its complement of skilled operator-observers to convey messages back and forth across the line.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The modern design of semaphores was first foreseen by the British polymath Robert Hooke, who first gave a vivid and comprehensive outline of visual telegraphy in a 1684 submission to the Royal Society.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] His proposal (which was motivated by military concerns following the Battle of Vienna the preceding year) was not put into practice during his lifetime.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The first operational optical semaphore line arrived in 1792, created by the French engineer Claude Chappe and his brothers, who succeeded in covering France with a network of 556 stations stretching a total distance of 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] It was used for military and national communications until the 1850s.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Many national services adopted signaling systems different from the Chappe system.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] For example, Britain and Sweden adopted systems of shuttered panels (in contradiction to the Chappe brothers' contention that angled rods are more visible).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] In Spain, the engineer Agustín de Betancourt developed his own system which was adopted by that state.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] This system was considered by many experts in Europe better than Chappe's, even in France.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] These systems were popular in the late 18th to early 19th century but could not compete with the electrical telegraph, and went completely out of service by 1880.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Semaphore flags are the system for conveying information at a distance by means of visual signals with hand-held flags, rods, disks, paddles, or occasionally bare or gloved hands.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Information is encoded by the position of the flags, objects or arms; it is read when they are in a fixed position.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Semaphores were adopted and widely used (with hand-held flags replacing the mechanical arms of shutter semaphores) in the maritime world in the 19th century.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] They are still used during underway replenishment at sea and are acceptable for emergency communication in daylight or, using lighted wands instead of flags, at night.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The newer flag semaphore system uses two short poles with square flags, which a signaler holds in different positions to convey letters of the alphabet and numbers.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The transmitter holds one pole in each hand, and extends each arm in one of eight possible directions.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Except for in the rest position, the flags cannot overlap.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The flags are colored differently based on whether the signals are sent by sea or by land.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] At sea, the flags are colored red and yellow (the Oscar flags), while on land, they are white and blue (the Papa flags).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Flags are not required, they just make the characters more obvious.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Signal lamps (such as Aldis lamps), are visual signaling devices for optical communication (typically using Morse code).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Modern signal lamps are a focused lamp which can produce a pulse of light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] In large versions this pulse is achieved by opening and closing shutters mounted in front of the lamp, either via a manually operated pressure switch or, in later versions, automatically.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] With hand held lamps, a concave mirror is tilted by a trigger to focus the light into pulses.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The lamps are usually equipped with some form of optical sight, and are most commonly deployed on naval vessels and also used in airport control towers with coded aviation light signals.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Aviation light signals are used in the case of a radio failure, an aircraft not equipped with a radio, or in the case of a hearing-impaired pilot.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Air traffic controllers have long used signal light guns to direct such aircraft.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The light gun's lamp has a focused bright beam capable of emitting three different colors: red, white and green.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] These colors may be flashing or steady, and provide different instructions to aircraft in flight or on the ground (for example, "cleared to land" or "cleared for takeoff").
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Pilots can acknowledge the instructions by wiggling their plane's wings, moving their ailerons if they are on the ground, or by flashing their landing or navigation lights during night time.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Only 12 simple standardized instructions are directed at aircraft using signal light guns as the system is not utilized with Morse code.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] A heliograph (Greek: Ἥλιος *helios*, meaning "sun", and γραφειν *graphein*, meaning "write") is a wireless solar telegraph that signals by flashes of sunlight (generally using Morse code) reflected by a mirror.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The flashes are produced by momentarily pivoting the mirror, or by interrupting the beam with a shutter.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The heliograph was a simple but effective instrument for instantaneous optical communication over long distances during the late 19th and early 20th century.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Its main uses were in military, surveys and forest protection work.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] They were standard issue in the British and Australian armies until the 1960s, and were used by the Pakistani army as late as 1975.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] In the present day a variety of electronic systems optically transmit and receive information carried by pulses of light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Fiber-optic communication cables are employed to carry electronic data and telephone traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Free-space optical communications are also used every day in various applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Optical fiber is the most common type of channel for optical communications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The transmitters in optical fiber links are generally light-emitting diodes (LEDs) or laser diodes.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Infrared light is used more commonly than visible light, because optical fibers transmit infrared wavelengths with less attenuation and dispersion.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The signal encoding is typically simple intensity modulation, although historically optical phase and frequency modulation have been demonstrated in the lab.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The need for periodic signal regeneration was largely superseded by the introduction of the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which extended link distances at significantly lower cost.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The commercial introduction of dense wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) in 1996 by Ciena Corp was the real start of optical networking.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] WDM is now the common basis of nearly every high-capacity optical system in the world.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The first optical communication systems were designed and delivered to the U.S.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Army and Chevron by Optelecom, Inc., the venture co-founded by Gordon Gould, the inventor of the optical amplifier and the laser.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The photophone (originally given an alternate name, radiophone) is a communication device which allowed for the transmission of speech on a beam of light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] It was invented jointly by Alexander Graham Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter on February 19, 1880, at Bell's 1325 'L' Street laboratory in Washington, D.C.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Both were later to become full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association, created and financed by Bell.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message of considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School to the window of Bell's laboratory, some 213 meters (about 700 ft) away.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Bell believed the photophone was his most important invention.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage starting in the 1980s.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] The master patent for the photophone (U.S. patent 235,199 *Apparatus for Signalling and Communicating, called Photophone*), was issued in December 1880, many decades before its principles came to have practical applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Free-space optics (FSO) systems are employed for 'last mile' telecommunications and can function over distances of several kilometers as long as there is a clear line of sight between the source and the destination, and the optical receiver can reliably decode the transmitted information.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Other free-space systems can provide high-data-rate, long-range links using small, low-mass, low-power-consumption subsystems which make them suitable for communications in space.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Various planned satellite constellations intended to provide global broadband coverage take advantage of these benefits and employ laser communication for inter-satellite links between the several hundred to thousand satellites effectively creating a space-based optical mesh network.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] More generally, transmission of unguided optical signals is known as optical wireless communications (OWC).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-communication] Examples include medium-range visible light communication and short-distance IrDA, using infrared LEDs.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] An **optical fiber**, or **optical fibre**, is a flexible glass or plastic fiber that can transmit light from one end to the other.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are widely used in fiber-optic communication, where they permit transmission over longer distances and at higher bandwidths (data transfer rates) than electrical cables.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are used instead of cables because signals travel along them with less loss and are immune to electromagnetic interference.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are also used for illumination and imaging, and are often wrapped in bundles so they may be used to carry light into, or images out of confined spaces, as in the case of a fiberscope.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Specially designed fibers are also used for a variety of other applications, such as fiber optic sensors and fiber lasers.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Glass optical fibers are typically made by drawing, while plastic fibers can be made either by drawing or by extrusion.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers typically include a core surrounded by a transparent cladding material with a lower index of refraction.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Light is kept in the core by the phenomenon of total internal reflection which causes the fiber to act as a waveguide.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers that support many propagation paths or transverse modes are called multi-mode fibers, while those that support a single mode are called single-mode fibers (SMF).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fibers generally have a wider core diameter and are used for short-distance communication links and for applications where high power must be transmitted.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode fibers are used for most communication links longer than 1,050 meters (3,440 ft).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Being able to join optical fibers with low loss is important in fiber optic communication.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This is more complex than joining electrical wire or cable and involves careful cleaving of the fibers, precise alignment of the fiber cores, and the coupling of these aligned cores.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] For applications that demand a permanent connection a fusion splice is common.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In this technique, an electric arc is used to melt the ends of the fibers together.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Another common technique is a mechanical splice, where the ends of the fibers are held in contact by mechanical force.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Temporary or semi-permanent connections are made by means of specialized optical fiber connectors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The field of applied science and engineering concerned with the design and application of optical fibers is known as *fiber optics*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The term was coined by Indian-American physicist Narinder Singh Kapany.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Daniel Colladon and Jacques Babinet first demonstrated the guiding of light by refraction, the principle that makes fiber optics possible, in Paris in the early 1840s.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] John Tyndall included a demonstration of it in his public lectures in London, 12 years later.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In the late 19th century, a team of Viennese doctors guided light through bent glass rods to illuminate body cavities.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Practical applications such as close internal illumination during dentistry followed, early in the twentieth century.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Image transmission through tubes was demonstrated independently by the radio experimenter Clarence Hansell and the television pioneer John Logie Baird in the 1920s.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In the 1930s, Heinrich Lamm showed that one could transmit images through a bundle of unclad optical fibers and used it for internal medical examinations, but his work was largely forgotten.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In 1953, Dutch scientist Bram van Heel first demonstrated image transmission through bundles of optical fibers with a transparent cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Later that same year, Harold Hopkins and Narinder Singh Kapany at Imperial College in London succeeded in making image-transmitting bundles with over 10,000 fibers, and subsequently achieved image transmission through a 75 cm long bundle which combined several thousand fibers.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The first practical fiber optic semi-flexible gastroscope was patented by Basil Hirschowitz, C.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Curtiss, researchers at the University of Michigan, in 1956.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In the process of developing the gastroscope, Curtiss produced the first glass-clad fibers; previous optical fibers had relied on air or impractical oils and waxes as the low-index cladding material.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Kapany coined the term *fiber optics* after writing a 1960 article in *Scientific American* that introduced the topic to a wide audience.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] He subsequently wrote the first book about the new field.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The first working fiber-optic data transmission system was demonstrated by German physicist Manfred Börner at Telefunken Research Labs in Ulm in 1965, followed by the first patent application for this technology in 1966.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In 1968, NASA used fiber optics in the television cameras that were sent to the moon.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] At the time, the use in the cameras was classified *confidential*, and employees handling the cameras had to be supervised by someone with an appropriate security clearance.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Hockham of the British company Standard Telephones and Cables (STC) were the first to promote the idea that the attenuation in optical fibers could be reduced below 20 decibels per kilometer (dB/km), making fibers a practical communication medium, in 1965.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] They proposed that the attenuation in fibers available at the time was caused by impurities that could be removed, rather than by fundamental physical effects such as scattering.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] They correctly and systematically theorized the light-loss properties for optical fiber and pointed out the right material to use for such fibers—silica glass with high purity.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This discovery earned Kao the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The crucial attenuation limit of 20 dB/km was first achieved in 1970 by researchers Robert D.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Schultz, and Frank Zimar working for American glass maker Corning Glass Works.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] They demonstrated a fiber with 17 dB/km attenuation by doping silica glass with titanium.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A few years later, they produced a fiber with only 4 dB/km attenuation using germanium dioxide as the core dopant.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In 1981, General Electric produced fused quartz ingots that could be drawn into strands 25 miles (40 km) long.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Initially, high-quality optical fibers could only be manufactured at two meters per second.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Chemical engineer Thomas Mensah joined Corning in 1983 and increased the speed of manufacture to over 50 meters per second, making optical fiber cables cheaper than traditional copper ones.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] These innovations ushered in the era of optical fiber telecommunication.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The Italian research center CSELT worked with Corning to develop practical optical fiber cables, resulting in the first metropolitan fiber optic cable being deployed in Turin in 1977.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] CSELT also developed an early technique for splicing optical fibers, called Springroove.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in modern optical cables is far less than in electrical copper cables, leading to long-haul fiber connections with repeater distances of 70–150 kilometers (43–93 mi).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Payne of the University of Southampton and Emmanuel Desurvire at Bell Labs, developed the erbium-doped fiber amplifier, which reduced the cost of long-distance fiber systems by reducing or eliminating optical-electrical-optical repeaters, in 1986 and 1987 respectively.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The emerging field of photonic crystals led to the development in 1991 of photonic-crystal fiber, which guides light by diffraction from a periodic structure, rather than by total internal reflection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The first photonic crystal fibers became commercially available in 2000.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic crystal fibers can carry higher power than conventional fibers and their wavelength-dependent properties can be manipulated to improve performance.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is used as a medium for telecommunication and computer networking because it is flexible and can be bundled as cables.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] It is especially advantageous for long-distance communications, because infrared light propagates through the fiber with much lower attenuation compared to electricity in electrical cables.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This allows long distances to be spanned with few repeaters.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A data transfer rate of 10 or 40 Gbit/s is typical in deployed systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Using wavelength-division multiplexing (WDM) enables each fiber to carry many independent channels, each using a different wavelength of light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The net data rate (data rate without overhead bytes) per fiber is the per-channel data rate reduced by the forward error correction (FEC) overhead, multiplied by the number of channels (usually up to 80 in commercial dense WDM systems as of 2008).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] For short-distance applications, such as a network in an office building (see fiber to the office), fiber-optic cabling can save space in cable ducts.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This is because a single fiber can carry much more data than electrical cables such as standard category 5 cable, which typically runs at 100 Mbit/s or 1 Gbit/s speeds.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers are often also used for short-distance connections between devices.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] For example, most high-definition televisions offer a digital audio optical connection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This allows the streaming of audio over light, using the S/PDIF protocol over an optical TOSLINK connection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber optic drones have been used in the Russo-Ukrainian War since March 2024.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] These types of drones are immune to electromagnetic interference and are not affected by electronic warfare systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The drones typically carry spools of glass fiber-optic cable ranging from 5 to 30 kilometres (3.1 to 18.6 mi) in length, with experimental configurations reported at up to 65 kilometres (40 mi).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Because the control signals and video feed travel through the glass core at the speed of light without generating radio emissions, the drones cannot be located or disabled by conventional radio-frequency jamming or direction-finding equipment.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Russia's Ushkuynik KVN was among the first mass-produced fiber-optic FPV loitering munitions, deployed from 2024 onward during the Russo-Ukrainian conflict.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A physical limitation of the technology is cable snagging: if the drone maneuvers sharply through dense terrain, the trailing glass cable can catch on vegetation or structures and snap, immediately ending the mission.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as light guides in medical and other applications where bright light needs to be shone on a target without a clear line-of-sight path.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Many microscopes use fiber-optic light sources to provide intense illumination of samples being studied.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In some buildings, optical fibers route sunlight from the roof to other parts of the building (see nonimaging optics).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical-fiber lamps are used for illumination in decorative applications, including signs, art, toys and artificial Christmas trees.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is an intrinsic part of the light-transmitting concrete building product LiTraCon.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The bundles are led from exterior/rooftop optical light collectors through small openings or cable ducts and carry the light to where it is needed.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The optical fibers end in hybrid luminaires where the sunlight is joined with electric light, either on demand or to automatically maintain a constant light level even as the available sunlight decreases.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers have many uses in remote sensing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In some applications, the fiber itself is the sensor (the fibers channel optical light to a processing device that analyzes changes in the light's characteristics).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In other cases, fiber is used to connect a sensor to a measurement system.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers can be used as sensors to measure strain, temperature, pressure, and other quantities by modifying a fiber so that the property being measured modulates the intensity, phase, polarization, wavelength, or transit time of light in the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Sensors that vary the intensity of light are the simplest since only a simple source and detector are required.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A particularly useful feature of such fiber optic sensors is that they can, if required, provide distributed sensing over distances of up to one meter.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed acoustic sensing is one example of this.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can also be used in structural health monitoring.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This type of sensor can detect stresses that may have a lasting impact on structures.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] It is based on the principle of measuring analog attenuation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, highly localized measurements can be provided by integrating miniaturized sensing elements with the tip of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] These can be implemented by various micro- and nanofabrication technologies, such that they do not exceed the microscopic boundary of the fiber tip, allowing for such applications as insertion into blood vessels via hypodermic needle.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic fiber optic sensors use an optical fiber cable, normally a multi-mode one, to transmit modulated light from either a non-fiber optical sensor—or an electronic sensor connected to an optical transmitter.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A major benefit of extrinsic sensors is their ability to reach otherwise inaccessible places.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] An example is the measurement of temperature inside jet engines by using a fiber to transmit radiation into a pyrometer outside the engine.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors can be used in the same way to measure the internal temperature of electrical transformers, where the extreme electromagnetic fields present make other measurement techniques impossible.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Extrinsic sensors measure vibration, rotation, displacement, velocity, acceleration, torque, and torsion.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A solid-state version of the gyroscope, using the interference of light, has been developed.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber optic gyroscope (FOG) has no moving parts and exploits the Sagnac effect to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Common uses for fiber optic sensors include advanced intrusion detection security systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The light is transmitted along a fiber optic sensor cable placed on a fence, pipeline, or communication cabling, and the returned signal is monitored and analyzed for disturbances.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This return signal is digitally processed to detect disturbances and trip an alarm if an intrusion has occurred.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are widely used as components of optical chemical sensors and optical biosensors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also used in imaging optics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A coherent bundle of fibers is used, sometimes along with lenses, for a long, thin imaging device called an endoscope, which is used to view objects through a small hole.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Medical endoscopes are used for minimally invasive exploratory or surgical procedures.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Industrial endoscopes (see fiberscope or borescope) are used for inspecting anything hard to reach, such as jet engine interiors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber can be used to transmit power using a photovoltaic cell to convert the light into electricity.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] While this method of power transmission is not as efficient as conventional ones, it is especially useful in situations where it is desirable not to have a metallic conductor as in the case of use near MRI machines, which produce strong magnetic fields.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Other examples are for powering electronics in high-powered antenna elements and measurement devices used in high-voltage transmission equipment.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In spectroscopy, optical fiber bundles transmit light from a spectrometer to a substance that cannot be placed inside the spectrometer itself, in order to analyze its composition.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A spectrometer analyzes substances by bouncing light off and through them.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] By using fibers, a spectrometer can be used to study objects remotely.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber doped with certain rare-earth elements such as erbium can be used as the gain medium of a fiber laser or optical amplifier.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Rare-earth-doped optical fibers can be used to provide signal amplification by splicing a short section of doped fiber into a regular (undoped) optical fiber line.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The doped fiber is optically pumped with a second laser wavelength that is coupled into the line in addition to the signal wave.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Both wavelengths of light are transmitted through the doped fiber, which transfers energy from the second pump wavelength to the signal wave.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The process that causes the amplification is stimulated emission.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fiber is also widely exploited as a nonlinear medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The glass medium supports a host of nonlinear optical interactions, and the long interaction lengths possible in fiber facilitate a variety of phenomena, which are harnessed for applications and fundamental investigation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Conversely, fiber nonlinearity can have deleterious effects on optical signals, and measures are often required to minimize such unwanted effects.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers doped with a wavelength shifter collect scintillation light in physics experiments.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber-optic sights for handguns, rifles, and shotguns use pieces of optical fiber to improve the visibility of markings on the sight.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are used as components in e-textiles.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This was first done by Harry Wainwright in the 1980s.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] An optical fiber is a cylindrical dielectric waveguide (nonconducting waveguide) that transmits light along its axis through the process of total internal reflection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The fiber consists of a *core* surrounded by a cladding layer, both of which are made of dielectric materials.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] To confine the optical signal in the core, the refractive index of the core must be greater than that of the cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The boundary between the core and cladding may either be abrupt, in *step-index fiber*, or gradual, in *graded-index fiber*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Light can be fed into optical fibers using lasers or LEDs.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers are immune to electrical interference as there is no cross-talk between signals in different cables and no pickup of environmental noise.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Information traveling inside the optical fiber is even immune to electromagnetic pulses generated by nuclear devices.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables do not conduct electricity, which makes them useful for protecting communications equipment in high voltage environments such as power generation facilities or applications prone to lightning strikes.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The electrical isolation also prevents problems with ground loops.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Because there is no electricity in optical cables that could potentially generate sparks, they can be used in environments where explosive fumes are present.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Wiretapping (in this case, fiber tapping) is more difficult compared to electrical connections.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber cables are not targeted for metal theft.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In contrast, copper cable systems use large amounts of copper and have been targeted since the 2000s commodities boom.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index is a way of measuring the speed of light in a material.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels fastest in a vacuum, such as in outer space.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The speed of light in vacuum is about 300,000 kilometers (186,000 miles) per second.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of a medium is calculated by dividing the speed of light in vacuum by the speed of light in that medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The refractive index of vacuum is therefore 1, by definition.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A typical single-mode fiber used for telecommunications has a cladding made of pure silica, with an index of 1.444 at 1500 nm, and a core of doped silica with an index around 1.4475.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The larger the index of refraction, the slower light travels in that medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] From this information, a simple rule of thumb is that a signal using optical fiber for communication will travel at around 200,000 kilometers per second.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Thus a phone call carried by fiber between Sydney and New York, a 16,000-kilometer distance, means that there is a minimum delay of 80 milliseconds (about ${\tfrac {1}{12}}$ of a second) between when one caller speaks and the other hears.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] When light traveling in an optically dense medium hits a boundary at a steep angle of incidence (larger than the critical angle for the boundary), the light is completely reflected.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This is called total internal reflection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This effect is used in optical fibers to confine light in the core.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Most modern optical fiber is *weakly guiding*, meaning that the difference in refractive index between the core and the cladding is very small (typically less than 1%).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Light travels through the fiber core, bouncing back and forth off the boundary between the core and cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Because the light must strike the boundary with an angle greater than the critical angle, only light that enters the fiber within a certain range of angles can travel down the fiber without leaking out.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This range of angles is called the acceptance cone of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] There is a maximum angle from the fiber axis at which light may enter the fiber so that it will propagate, or travel, in the core of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The sine of this maximum angle is the numerical aperture (NA) of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber with a larger NA requires less precision to splice and work with than fiber with a smaller NA.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The size of this acceptance cone is a function of the refractive index difference between the fiber's core and cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Optical fibers with a large core diameter (greater than 10 micrometers) may be analyzed by geometrical optics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Such fibers are called *multi-mode fibers*, from the electromagnetic analysis (see below).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In a step-index multi-mode fiber, rays of light are guided along the fiber core by total internal reflection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the core-cladding boundary at an angle (measured relative to a line normal to the boundary) greater than the critical angle for this boundary, are completely reflected.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle is determined by the difference in the index of refraction between the core and cladding materials.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Rays that meet the boundary at a low angle are refracted from the core into the cladding where they terminate.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The critical angle determines the acceptance angle of the fiber, often reported as a numerical aperture.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A high numerical aperture allows light to propagate down the fiber in rays both close to the axis and at various angles, allowing efficient coupling of light into the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] However, this high numerical aperture increases the amount of dispersion as rays at different angles have different path lengths and therefore take different amounts of time to traverse the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In graded-index fiber, the index of refraction in the core decreases continuously between the axis and the cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This causes light rays to bend smoothly as they approach the cladding, rather than reflecting abruptly from the core-cladding boundary.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The resulting curved paths reduce multi-path dispersion because high-angle rays pass more through the lower-index periphery of the core, rather than the high-index center.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The index profile is chosen to minimize the difference in axial propagation speeds of the various rays in the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This ideal index profile is very close to a parabolic relationship between the index and the distance from the axis.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fibers with a core diameter less than about ten times the wavelength of the propagating light cannot be modeled using geometric optics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, they must be analyzed as an electromagnetic waveguide structure, according to Maxwell's equations as reduced to the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] As an optical waveguide, the fiber supports one or more confined transverse modes by which light can propagate along the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fiber supporting only one mode is called *single-mode*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The waveguide analysis shows that the light energy in the fiber is not completely confined in the core.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Instead, especially in single-mode fibers, a significant fraction of the energy in the bound mode travels in the cladding as an evanescent wave.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The most common type of single-mode fiber has a core diameter of 8–10 micrometers and is designed for use in the near infrared.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Multi-mode fiber, by comparison, is manufactured with core diameters as small as 50 micrometers and as large as hundreds of micrometers.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Some special-purpose optical fiber is constructed with a non-cylindrical core or cladding layer, usually with an elliptical or rectangular cross-section.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] These include polarization-maintaining fiber used in fiber optic sensors and fiber designed to suppress whispering gallery mode propagation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Photonic-crystal fiber is made with a regular pattern of index variation (often in the form of cylindrical holes that run along the length of the fiber).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Such fiber uses diffraction effects instead of or in addition to total internal reflection, to confine light to the fiber's core.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The properties of the fiber can be tailored to a wide variety of applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in fiber optics, also known as transmission loss, is the reduction in the intensity of the light signal as it travels through the transmission medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation coefficients in fiber optics are usually expressed in units of dB/km.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The medium is usually a fiber of silica glass that confines the incident light beam within.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation is an important factor limiting the transmission of a digital signal across large distances.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Thus, much research has gone into both limiting the attenuation and maximizing the amplification of the optical signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Single-mode optical fibers can be made with extremely low loss.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Corning's Vascade® EX2500 fiber, a low loss single-mode fiber for telecommunications wavelengths, has a nominal attenuation of 0.148 dB/km at 1550 nm.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] A 10 km length of such fiber transmits nearly 71% of optical energy at 1550 nm.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation in optical fiber is caused primarily by both scattering and absorption.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In fibers based on fluoride glasses such as ZBLAN, minimum attenuation is limited by impurity absorption.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The vast majority of optical fibers are based on silica glass, where impurity absorption is negligible.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In silica fibers attenuation is determined by intrinsic mechanisms: Rayleigh scattering and infrared absorption in the glasses through which the light is propagating.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Absorption in silica increases steeply at wavelengths above 1570 nm.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] At wavelengths most useful for telecommunications, Rayleigh scattering is the dominant loss mechanism.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] At 1550 nm attenuation components for a record low loss fiber are given as follows: Rayleigh scattering loss: 0.1200 dB/km, infrared absorption loss: 0.0150 dB/km, impurity absorption loss: 0.0047 dB/km, waveguide imperfection loss: 0.0010 dB/km.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The propagation of light through the core of an optical fiber is based on the total internal reflection of the lightwave, in terms of geometric optics, or guided modes, in terms of electromagnetic waveguide.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In a typical single mode optical fiber about 75% of light is propagating through the core material, having higher refractive index, and about 25% of light is propagating through the cladding, having lower refractive index.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The interface between the core and cladding glasses is exceptionally smooth and does not give rise to a significant scattering loss or a waveguide imperfection loss.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering loss originates primarily from the Rayleigh scattering in the bulk of the glasses composing the fiber core and cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The scattering of light in optical quality glass fiber is caused by molecular level irregularities (compositional fluctuations) in the glass structure.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Indeed, one emerging school of thought is that glass is simply the limiting case of a polycrystalline solid.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Within this framework, *domains* exhibiting various degrees of short-range order become the building blocks of metals as well as glasses and ceramics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Distributed both between and within these domains are micro-structural defects that provide the most ideal locations for light scattering.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Scattering depends on the wavelength of the light being scattered and on the size of the scattering centers.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Angular dependence of the light intensity scattered from an optical fiber matched that of Rayleigh scattering, indicating that the scattering centers are much smaller than the wavelength of propagating light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] It originates from the density fluctuations driven by fictive temperature of the glass, and from the concentration fluctuations of dopants in both the core and the cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Rayleigh scattering coefficient, *R*, can be presented as : $R=R_{\text{d}}+R_{\text{c}}$ where *R*d represents Rayleigh scattering on density fluctuations and *R*c represents Rayleigh scattering on dopant concentration fluctuations.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The only physically significant variable affecting scattering on density fluctuations is the fictive temperature of the glass, lower fictive temperature results in a more homogeneous glass and lower Rayleigh scattering.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Fictive temperature may be dramatically reduced by about 100 wt. ppm of alkali oxide dopant in the fiber core, as well as slower cooling of the fiber during the fiber draw process.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] These approaches are used to produce optical fibers with the lowest attenuation, especially those for submarine telecom cables.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] For small dopant concentrations, *R*c is proportional to *x*(d*n*/d*x*)2, where x is the mole fraction of the dopant in SiO2-based glass and n is the refractive index of the glass.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] When GeO2 dopant is used to increase the refractive index of the fiber core, it increases the concentration fluctuation component of Rayleigh scattering, and attenuation of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This is why the lowest attenuation fibers do not use GeO2 in the core, and use fluorine in the cladding, to reduce the refractive index of the cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] *R*c in pure silica core fiber is proportional to the overlap integral between LP01 mode and fluorine-induced concentration fluctuation component in the cladding.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In the core of potassium-doped pure silica-core (KPSC) fiber only density fluctuations play a significant role, as the concentrations of K2O, fluorine and chlorine are very low.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The density fluctuations in the core are moderated by lower fictive temperature resulting from potassium doping, and are further reduced by annealing during the fiber draw process.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] This differs from the cladding, where higher fluorine dopant levels and the resulting concentration fluctuations add to the loss.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In such fibers the light travelling through the core experiences lower scattering and lower attenuation compared to the light propagating through the cladding segment of the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] At high optical powers, scattering can also be caused by nonlinear optical processes in the fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In addition to light scattering, attenuation or signal loss can also occur due to selective absorption of specific wavelengths.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The design of any optically transparent device requires the selection of materials based upon knowledge of its properties and limitations.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The crystal structure absorption characteristics observed at the lower frequency regions (mid- to far-IR wavelength range) define the long-wavelength transparency limit of the material.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] They are the result of the interactive coupling between the motions of thermally induced vibrations of the constituent atoms and molecules of the solid lattice and the incident light wave radiation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Hence, all materials are bounded by limiting regions of absorption caused by atomic and molecular vibrations (bond-stretching) in the far-infrared (>10 μm).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] In other words, the selective absorption of IR light by a particular material occurs because the selected frequency of the light wave matches the frequency (or an integer multiple of the frequency, i.e. harmonic) at which the particles of that material vibrate.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Since different atoms and molecules have different natural frequencies of vibration, they will selectively absorb different frequencies (or portions of the spectrum) of IR light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Reflection and transmission of light waves occur because the frequencies of the light waves do not match the natural resonant frequencies of vibration of the objects.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] When IR light of these frequencies strikes an object, the energy is either reflected or transmitted.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Attenuation over a cable run is significantly increased by the inclusion of connectors and splices.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Connectors typically introduce 0.3 dB per connector on well-polished connectors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] Splices typically introduce less than 0.2 dB per splice.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] where the dB loss per kilometer is a function of the type of fiber and can be found in the manufacturer's specifications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] For example, a typical 1550 nm single-mode fiber has a loss of 0.3 dB per kilometer.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p01] The calculated loss budget is used when testing to confirm that the measured loss is within the normal operating parameters.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Glass optical fibers are almost always made from silica, but some other materials, such as fluorozirconate, fluoroaluminate, and chalcogenide glasses as well as crystalline materials like sapphire, are used for longer-wavelength infrared or other specialized applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica and fluoride glasses usually have refractive indices of about 1.5, but some materials such as the chalcogenides can have indices as high as 3.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the index difference between core and cladding is less than one percent.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Plastic optical fibers (POF) are commonly step-index multi-mode fibers with a core diameter of 0.5 millimeters or larger.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] POF typically have higher attenuation coefficients than glass fibers, 1 dB/m or higher, and this high attenuation limits the range of POF-based systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica exhibits fairly good optical transmission over a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In the near-infrared (near IR) portion of the spectrum, particularly around 1.5 μm, silica can have extremely low absorption and scattering losses of the order of 0.2 dB/km.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses depend on using ultra-pure silica.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A high transparency in the 1.4-μm region is achieved by maintaining a low concentration of hydroxyl groups (OH).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Alternatively, a high OH concentration is better for transmission in the ultraviolet (UV) region.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica can be drawn into fibers at reasonably high temperatures and has a fairly broad glass transformation range.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] One other advantage is that fusion splicing and cleaving of silica fibers is relatively effective.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also has high mechanical strength against both pulling and even bending, provided that the fiber is not too thick and that the surfaces have been well prepared during processing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Even simple cleaving of the ends of the fiber can provide nicely flat surfaces with acceptable optical quality.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica is also relatively chemically inert.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In particular, it is not hygroscopic (does not absorb water).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica glass can be doped with various materials.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] One purpose of doping is to raise the refractive index (e.g. with germanium dioxide (GeO2) or aluminium oxide (Al2O3)) or to lower it (e.g. with fluorine or boron trioxide (B2O3)).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Doping is also possible with laser-active ions (for example, rare-earth-doped fibers) in order to obtain active fibers to be used, for example, in fiber amplifiers or laser applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Both the fiber core and cladding are typically doped, so that the entire assembly (core and cladding) is effectively the same compound (e.g. an aluminosilicate, germanosilicate, phosphosilicate or borosilicate glass).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Particularly for active fibers, pure silica is usually not a very suitable host glass, because it exhibits a low solubility for rare-earth ions.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This can lead to quenching effects due to the clustering of dopant ions.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Aluminosilicates are much more effective in this respect.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Silica fiber also exhibits a high threshold for optical damage.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This property ensures a low tendency for laser-induced breakdown.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This is important for fiber amplifiers when utilized for the amplification of short pulses.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Because of these properties, silica fibers are the material of choice in many optical applications, such as communications (except for very short distances with plastic optical fiber), fiber lasers, fiber amplifiers, and fiber-optic sensors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Large efforts put forth in the development of various types of silica fibers have further increased the performance of such fibers over other materials.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride glass is a class of non-oxide optical quality glasses composed of fluorides of various metals.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the low viscosity of these glasses, it is very difficult to completely avoid crystallization while processing it through the glass transition (or drawing the fiber from the melt).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Thus, although heavy metal fluoride glasses (HMFG) exhibit very low optical attenuation, they are not only difficult to manufacture, but are quite fragile, and have poor resistance to moisture and other environmental attacks.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Their best attribute is that they lack the absorption band associated with the hydroxyl (OH) group (3,200–3,600 cm−1; i.e., 2,777–3,125 nm or 2.78–3.13 μm), which is present in nearly all oxide-based glasses.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Such low losses were never realized in practice, and the fragility and high cost of fluoride fibers made them less than ideal as primary candidates.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers are used in mid-IR spectroscopy, fiber optic sensors, thermometry, and imaging.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fluoride fibers can be used for guided lightwave transmission in media such as YAG (yttrium aluminium garnet) lasers at 2.9 μm, as required for medical applications (e.g. ophthalmology and dentistry).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] An example of a heavy metal fluoride glass is the ZBLAN glass group, composed of zirconium, barium, lanthanum, aluminium, and sodium fluorides.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Their main technological application is as optical waveguides in both planar and fiber forms.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] They are advantageous especially in the mid-infrared (2,000–5,000 nm) range.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glass is a class of optical glasses composed of metaphosphates of various metals.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Instead of the SiO4 tetrahedra in the network solid structure of silicate glasses, the building block for this glass is phosphorus pentoxide (P2O5), which crystallizes in at least four different forms.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The most familiar polymorph is the cagelike structure of P4O10.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Phosphate glasses can be advantageous over silica glasses for optical fibers with a high concentration of doping rare-earth ions.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A mix of fluoride glass and phosphate glass is fluorophosphate glass.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The chalcogens—the elements in group 16 of the periodic table—particularly sulfur (S), selenium (Se) and tellurium (Te)—react with more electropositive elements, such as silver, to form chalcogenides.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] These are extremely versatile compounds, in that they can be crystalline or amorphous, metallic or semiconducting, and conductors of ions or electrons.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Chalcogenide glass can be used to make fibers for far infrared transmission.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Standard optical fibers are made by first constructing a large-diameter *preform* with a carefully controlled refractive index profile, and then *pulling* the preform to form the long, thin optical fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The preform is commonly made by three chemical vapor deposition methods: *inside vapor deposition*, *outside vapor deposition*, and *vapor axial deposition*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] With *inside vapor deposition*, the preform starts as a hollow glass tube approximately 40 centimeters (16 in) long, which is placed horizontally and rotated slowly on a lathe.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Gases such as silicon tetrachloride (SiCl4) or germanium tetrachloride (GeCl4) are injected with oxygen in the end of the tube.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The gases are then heated by means of an external hydrogen burner, bringing the temperature of the gas up to 1,900 K (1,600 °C, 3,000 °F), where the tetrachlorides react with oxygen to produce silica or germanium dioxide particles.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] When the reaction conditions are chosen to allow this reaction to occur in the gas phase throughout the tube volume, in contrast to earlier techniques where the reaction occurred only on the glass surface, this technique is called *modified chemical vapor deposition*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The oxide particles then agglomerate to form large particle chains, which subsequently deposit on the walls of the tube as soot.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The deposition is due to the large difference in temperature between the gas core and the wall causing the gas to push the particles outward in a process known as thermophoresis.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The torch is then traversed up and down the length of the tube to deposit the material evenly.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] After the torch has reached the end of the tube, it is then brought back to the beginning of the tube and the deposited particles are then melted to form a solid layer.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This process is repeated until a sufficient amount of material has been deposited.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For each layer the composition can be modified by varying the gas composition, resulting in precise control of the finished fiber's optical properties.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition or vapor axial deposition, the glass is formed by *flame hydrolysis*, a reaction in which silicon tetrachloride and germanium tetrachloride are oxidized by reaction with water in an oxyhydrogen flame.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In outside vapor deposition, the glass is deposited onto a solid rod, which is removed before further processing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In vapor axial deposition, a short *seed rod* is used, and a porous preform, whose length is not limited by the size of the source rod, is built up on its end.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The porous preform is consolidated into a transparent, solid preform by heating to about 1,800 K (1,500 °C, 2,800 °F).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Typical communications fiber uses a circular preform.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For some applications such as double-clad fibers another form is preferred.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In fiber lasers based on double-clad fiber, an asymmetric shape improves the filling factor for laser pumping.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Because of the surface tension, the shape is smoothed during the drawing process, and the shape of the resulting fiber does not reproduce the sharp edges of the preform.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Nevertheless, careful polishing of the preform is important, since any defects of the preform surface affect the optical and mechanical properties of the resulting fiber.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The preform, regardless of construction, is placed in a device known as a drawing tower, where the preform tip is heated and the optical fiber is pulled out as a string.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The tension on the fiber can be controlled to maintain the desired fiber thickness.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The light is guided down the core of the fiber by an optical cladding with a lower refractive index that traps light in the core through total internal reflection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For some types of fiber, the cladding is made of glass and is drawn along with the core from a preform with radially varying index of refraction.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For other types of fiber, the cladding is made of plastic and is applied like a coating (see below).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The cladding is coated by a buffer, (not to be confused with an actual buffer tube), that protects it from moisture and physical damage.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] These coatings are UV-cured urethane acrylate composite or polyimide materials applied to the outside of the fiber during the drawing process.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The coatings protect the very delicate strands of glass fiber—about the size of a human hair—and allow it to survive the rigors of manufacturing, proof testing, cabling, and installation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The buffer coating must be stripped off the fiber for termination or splicing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Today's glass optical fiber draw processes employ a dual-layer coating approach.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] An inner primary coating is designed to act as a shock absorber to minimize attenuation caused by microbending.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] An outer secondary coating protects the primary coating against mechanical damage and acts as a barrier to lateral forces, and may be colored to differentiate strands in bundled cable constructions.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] These fiber optic coating layers are applied during the fiber draw, at speeds approaching 100 kilometers per hour (60 mph).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings are applied using one of two methods: *wet-on-dry* and *wet-on-wet*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-dry, the fiber passes through a primary coating application, which is then UV cured, then through the secondary coating application, which is subsequently cured.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In wet-on-wet, the fiber passes through both the primary and secondary coating applications, then goes to UV curing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The thickness of the coating is taken into account when calculating the stress that the fiber experiences under different bend configurations.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In a two-point bend configuration, a coated fiber is bent in a U-shape and placed between the grooves of two faceplates, which are brought together until the fiber breaks.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The stress in the fiber in this configuration is given by $\sigma =1.198E{d_{\text{f}} \over d-d_{\text{c}}},$ where d is the distance between the faceplates.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The coefficient 1.198 is a geometric constant associated with this configuration.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber optic coatings protect the glass fibers from scratches that could lead to strength degradation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The combination of moisture and scratches accelerates the aging and deterioration of fiber strength.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] When fiber is subjected to low stresses over a long period, fiber fatigue can occur.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Over time or in extreme conditions, these factors combine to cause microscopic flaws in the glass fiber to propagate, which can ultimately result in fiber failure.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Three key characteristics of fiber optic waveguides can be affected by environmental conditions: strength, attenuation, and resistance to losses caused by microbending.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] External optical fiber cable jackets and buffer tubes protect glass optical fiber from environmental conditions that can affect the fiber's performance and long-term durability.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] On the inside, coatings ensure the reliability of the signal being carried and help minimize attenuation due to microbending.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In practical fibers, the cladding is usually coated with a tough resin and features an additional *buffer* layer, which may be further surrounded by a *jacket* layer, usually plastic.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] These layers add strength to the fiber but do not affect its optical properties.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Rigid fiber assemblies sometimes put light-absorbing glass between the fibers, to prevent light that leaks out of one fiber from entering another.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This reduces crosstalk between the fibers, or reduces flare in fiber bundle imaging applications.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Multi-fiber cable usually uses colored buffers to identify each strand.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Modern cables come in a wide variety of sheathings and armor, designed for applications such as direct burial in trenches, high voltage isolation, dual use as power lines, installation in conduit, lashing to aerial telephone poles, submarine installation, and insertion in paved streets.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Some fiber optic cable versions are reinforced with aramid yarns or glass yarns as an intermediary strength member.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In commercial terms, usage of the glass yarns are more cost-effective with no loss of mechanical durability.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Glass yarns also protect the cable core against rodents and termites.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fiber cable can be very flexible, but traditional fiber's loss increases greatly if the fiber is bent with a radius smaller than around 30 mm.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This creates a problem when the cable is bent around corners.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] *Bendable fibers*, targeted toward easier installation in home environments, have been standardized as ITU-T G.657.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This type of fiber can be bent with a radius as low as 7.5 mm without adverse impact.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Even more bendable fibers have been developed.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Bendable fiber may also be resistant to fiber hacking, in which the signal in a fiber is surreptitiously monitored by bending the fiber and detecting the leakage.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Another important feature of cable is cable's ability to withstand tension which determines how much force can be applied to the cable during installation.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers are connected to terminal equipment by optical fiber connectors.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] These connectors are usually of a standard type such as *FC*, *SC*, *ST*, *LC*, *MTRJ*, *MPO* or *SMA*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Optical fibers may be connected by connectors typically on a patch panel, or permanently by splicing, that is, joining two fibers together to form a continuous optical waveguide.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The generally accepted splicing method is fusion splicing, which melts the fiber ends together.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For quicker fastening jobs, a *mechanical splice* is used.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] All splicing techniques involve installing an enclosure that protects the splice.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fusion splicing is done with a specialized instrument.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are first stripped of their protective polymer coating (as well as the more sturdy outer jacket, if present).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The ends are cleaved with a precision cleaver to make them perpendicular, and are placed into special holders in the fusion splicer.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The splice is usually inspected via a magnified viewing screen to check the cleaves before and fusion after the splice.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The splicer uses small motors to align the end faces together, and emits a small spark between electrodes at the gap to burn off dust and moisture.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Then the splicer generates a larger spark that raises the temperature above the melting point of the glass, fusing the ends permanently.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The location and energy of the spark is carefully controlled so that the molten core and cladding do not mix, and this minimizes optical loss.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A splice loss estimate is measured by the splicer by directing light through the cladding on one side and measuring the light leaking from the cladding on the other side.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The complexity of this process makes fiber splicing much more difficult than splicing copper wire.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical fiber splices are designed to be quicker and easier to install, but there is still the need for stripping, careful cleaning, and precision cleaving.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The fiber ends are aligned and held together by a precision sleeve, often using a clear index-matching gel that enhances the transmission of light across the joint.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Mechanical splices typically have a higher optical loss and are less robust than fusion splices, especially if the gel is used.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers are terminated in connectors that hold the fiber end precisely and securely.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] An optical fiber connector is a rigid cylindrical barrel surrounded by a sleeve that holds the barrel in its mating socket.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The mating mechanism can be *push and click*, *turn and latch* (*bayonet mount*), or *screw-in* (*threaded*).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The barrel is typically free to move within the sleeve and may have a key that prevents the barrel and fiber from rotating as the connectors are mated.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A typical connector is installed by preparing the fiber end and inserting it into the rear of the connector body.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Quick-set adhesive is usually used to hold the fiber securely, and a strain relief is secured to the rear.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Once the adhesive sets, the fiber's end is polished.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Various polish profiles are used, depending on the type of fiber and the application.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The resulting signal strength loss is called *gap loss*.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For single-mode fiber, fiber ends are typically polished with a slight curvature that makes the mated connectors touch only at their cores.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This is called a *physical contact* (PC) polish.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The curved surface may be polished at an angle, to make an *angled physical contact (APC)* connection.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Such connections have higher loss than PC connections but greatly reduced back reflection because light that reflects from the angled surface leaks out of the fiber core.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] APC fiber ends have low back reflection even when disconnected.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In the 1990s, the number of parts per connector, polishing of the fibers, and the need to oven-bake the epoxy in each connector made terminating fiber optic cables difficult.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Today, connector types on the market offer easier, less labor-intensive ways of terminating cables.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Some of the most popular connectors are pre-polished at the factory and include a gel inside the connector.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A cleave is made at a required length, to get as close to the polished piece already inside the connector.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The gel surrounds the point where the two pieces meet inside the connector for very little light loss.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] For the most demanding installations, factory pre-polished pigtails of sufficient length to reach the first fusion splice enclosure assures good performance and minimizes on-site labor.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] It is often necessary to align an optical fiber with another optical fiber or with an optoelectronic device such as a light-emitting diode, a laser diode, or a modulator.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This can involve either carefully aligning the fiber and placing it in contact with the device, or can use a lens to allow coupling over an air gap.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Typically the size of the fiber mode is much larger than the size of the mode in a laser diode or a silicon optical chip.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In this case, a tapered or lensed fiber is used to match the fiber mode field distribution to that of the other element.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The lens on the end of the fiber can be formed using polishing, laser cutting or fusion splicing.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In a laboratory environment, a bare fiber end is coupled using a fiber launch system, which uses a microscope objective lens to focus the light down to a fine point.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] A precision translation stage (micro-positioning table) is used to move the lens, fiber, or device to allow the coupling efficiency to be optimized.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Fibers with a connector on the end make this process much simpler: the connector is simply plugged into a pre-aligned fiber-optic collimator, which contains a lens that is either accurately positioned to the fiber or is adjustable.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] To achieve the best injection efficiency into a single-mode fiber, the direction, position, size, and divergence of the beam must all be optimized.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] With good optimization, 70 to 90% coupling efficiency can be achieved.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] With properly polished single-mode fibers, the emitted beam has an almost perfect Gaussian shape—even in the far field—if a good lens is used.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The lens needs to be large enough to support the full numerical aperture of the fiber, and must not introduce aberrations in the beam.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] At optical intensities above two megawatts per square centimeter, when a fiber is subjected to a shock or is otherwise suddenly damaged, a *fiber fuse* can occur.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The reflection from the damage vaporizes the fiber immediately before the break, and this new defect remains reflective so that the damage propagates back toward the transmitter at 1–3 meters per second (4–11 km/h, 2–8 mph).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The open fiber control system, which ensures laser eye safety in the event of a broken fiber, can also effectively halt propagation of the fiber fuse.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] In situations, such as undersea cables, where high power levels might be used without the need for open fiber control, a fiber fuse protection device at the transmitter can break the circuit to minimize damage.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] The refractive index of fibers varies slightly with the frequency of light, and light sources are not perfectly monochromatic.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Chromatic dispersion arises from both the waveguide structure of the fiber and the dispersive properties of the glass itself, with the latter contribution typically being dominant.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] Modulation of the light source to transmit a signal also slightly widens the frequency band of the transmitted light.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This has the effect that, over long distances and at high modulation speeds, different portions of light can take different times to arrive at the receiver, ultimately making the signal impossible to discern.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-fiber-p02] This problem can be overcome in several ways, including the use of extra repeaters and the use of a relatively short length of fiber that has the opposite refractive index gradient.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] An **optical transport network** (**OTN**) is a digital wrapper that encapsulates frames of data, to allow multiple data sources to be sent on the same channel.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] This creates an optical virtual private network for each client signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] ITU-T defines an optical transport network as a set of optical network elements (ONE) connected by optical fiber links, able to provide functionality of transport, multiplexing, switching, management, supervision and survivability of optical channels carrying client signals.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] An ONE may re-time, re-Amplify, re-shape (3R) but it does not have to be 3R – it can be purely photonic.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] Unless connected by optical fibre links, it shall not be OTN.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] Mere functionality of switching, management, supervision shall not make it OTN, unless the signals are carried through optical fibre.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] Unlike SONET/SDH, OTN provides a mechanism to manage multiplexed wavelengths in a DWDM system.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] OTN was designed to provide higher throughput (currently 400G) than its predecessor SONET/SDH, which stops at 40 Gbit/s, per channel.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] ITU-T Recommendation G.709 is commonly called Optical Transport Network (OTN) (also called **digital wrapper technology** or **optical channel wrapper**).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] As of December 2009, OTN has standardized the following line rates.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] (LAN) PHY coming from IP/Ethernet switches and routers at full line rate (10.3 Gbit/s).
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] develop for transport of 10G LAN PHY, and one for 10G WAN PHY, over SDH and OTN.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] The OTUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is an information structure into which another information structure called ODUk (k=1/2/2e/3/3e2/4) is mapped.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] The ODUk signal is the server layer signal for client signals.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] The OTN signals at all data-rates have the same frame structure but the frame period reduces as the data-rate increases.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] As a result, the Time-Slot Interchange (TSI) technique of implementing SONET/SDH switch fabrics is not directly applicable to OTN switch fabrics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] OTN switch fabrics are typically implemented using Packet Switch Fabrics.
[src:sonet-sdh/optical-transport-network] On a point-to-point OTN link there is latency due to forward error correction (FEC) processing.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET and SDH, which are essentially the same, were originally designed to transport circuit mode communications, e.g.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] DS1, DS3, from a variety of different sources.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] However, they were primarily designed to support real-time, uncompressed, circuit-switched voice encoded in PCM format.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The primary difficulty in doing this prior to SONET/SDH was that the synchronization sources of these various circuits were different.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This meant that each circuit was actually operating at a slightly different rate and with different phase.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET/SDH allowed for the simultaneous transport of many different circuits of differing origin within a single framing protocol.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET/SDH is not a complete communications protocol in itself, but a transport protocol (not a "transport" in the OSI Model sense).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Due to SONET/SDH's essential protocol neutrality and transport-oriented features, SONET/SDH was the choice for transporting the fixed length Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) frames also known as cells.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It quickly evolved mapping structures and concatenated payload containers to transport ATM connections.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Both SDH and SONET are widely used today: SONET in the United States and Canada, and SDH in the rest of the world.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Although the SONET standards were developed before SDH, it is considered a variation of SDH because of SDH's greater worldwide market penetration.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET is subdivided into four sublayers with some factor such as the path, line, section and physical layer.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SDH standard was originally defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI), and is formalised as International Telecommunication Union (ITU) standards G.707, G.783, G.784, and G.803.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SONET standard was defined by Telcordia and American National Standards Institute (ANSI) standard T1.105. which define the set of transmission formats and transmission rates in the range above 51.840 Mbit/s.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SDH differs from Plesiochronous Digital Hierarchy (PDH) in that the exact rates that are used to transport the data on SONET/SDH are tightly synchronized across the entire network, using atomic clocks.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This synchronization system allows entire inter-country networks to operate synchronously, greatly reducing the amount of buffering required between elements in the network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Both SONET and SDH can be used to encapsulate earlier digital transmission standards, such as the PDH standard, or they can be used to directly support either Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) or so-called packet over SONET/SDH (POS) networking.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Therefore, it is inaccurate to think of SDH or SONET as communications protocols in and of themselves; they are generic, all-purpose transport containers for moving both voice and data.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The basic format of a SONET/SDH signal allows it to carry many different services in its virtual container (VC), because it is bandwidth-flexible.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET and SDH often use different terms to describe identical features or functions.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This can cause confusion and exaggerate their differences.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] With a few exceptions, SDH can be thought of as a superset of SONET.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET is a set of transport containers that allow for delivery of a variety of protocols, including traditional telephony, ATM, Ethernet, and TCP/IP traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET therefore is not in itself a native communications protocol and should not be confused as being necessarily connection-oriented in the way that term is usually used.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The protocol is a heavily multiplexed structure, with the header interleaved between the data in a complex way.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This permits the encapsulated data to have its own frame rate and be able to "float around" relative to the SDH/SONET frame structure and rate.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This interleaving permits a very low latency for the encapsulated data.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Data passing through equipment can be delayed by at most 32 μs, compared to a frame rate of 125 μs; in many competing protocols, which buffer the data during such transits for at least one frame or packet before sending it on.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Extra padding is allowed for the multiplexed data to move within the overall framing, as the data is clocked at a different rate than the frame rate.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The protocol is made more complex by the decision to permit this padding at most levels of the multiplexing structure, but it improves all-around performance.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The basic unit of framing in SDH is a STM-1 (Synchronous Transport Module, level 1), which operates at 155.520 megabits per second (Mbit/s).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET refers to this basic unit as an STS-3c (Synchronous Transport Signal 3, concatenated).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] When the STS-3c is carried over OC-3, it is often colloquially referred to as OC-3c, but this is not an official designation within the SONET standard as there is no physical layer (i.e. optical) difference between an STS-3c and 3 STS-1s carried within an OC-3.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET offers an additional basic unit of transmission, the STS-1 (Synchronous Transport Signal 1) or OC-1, operating at 51.84 Mbit/s—exactly one third of an STM-1/STS-3c/OC-3c carrier.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This speed is dictated by the bandwidth requirements for PCM-encoded telephonic voice signals: at this rate, an STS-1/OC-1 circuit can carry the bandwidth equivalent of a standard DS-3 channel, which can carry 672 64-kbit/s voice channels.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In SONET, the STS-3c signal is composed of three multiplexed STS-1 signals; the STS-3c may be carried on an OC-3 signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Some manufacturers also support the SDH equivalent of the STS-1/OC-1, known as STM-0.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In packet-oriented data transmission, such as Ethernet, a packet frame usually consists of a header and a payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The header is transmitted first, followed by the payload (and possibly a trailer, such as a CRC).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In synchronous optical networking, this is modified slightly.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The header is termed the *overhead*, and instead of being transmitted before the payload, is interleaved with it during transmission.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Part of the overhead is transmitted, then part of the payload, then the next part of the overhead, then the next part of the payload, until the entire frame has been transmitted.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In the case of an STS-1, the frame is 810 octets in size, while the STM-1/STS-3c frame is 2,430 octets in size.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For STS-1, the frame is transmitted as three octets of overhead, followed by 87 octets of payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This is repeated nine times, until 810 octets have been transmitted, taking 125 μs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In the case of an STS-3c/STM-1, which operates three times faster than an STS-1, nine octets of overhead are transmitted, followed by 261 octets of payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This is also repeated nine times until 2,430 octets have been transmitted, also taking 125 μs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For both SONET and SDH, this is often represented by displaying the frame graphically: as a block of 90 columns and nine rows for STS-1, and 270 columns and nine rows for STM1/STS-3c.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This representation aligns all the overhead columns, so the overhead appears as a contiguous block, as does the payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The internal structure of the overhead and payload within the frame differs slightly between SONET and SDH, and different terms are used in the standards to describe these structures.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Their standards are extremely similar in implementation, making it easy to interoperate between SDH and SONET at any given bandwidth.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In practice, the terms STS-1 and OC-1 are sometimes used interchangeably, though the OC designation refers to the signal in its optical form.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It is therefore incorrect to say that an OC-3 contains 3 OC-1s: an OC-3 can be said to contain 3 STS-1s.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The Synchronous Transport Module, level 1 (STM-1) frame is the basic transmission format for SDH—the first level of the synchronous digital hierarchy.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The STM-1 frame is transmitted in exactly 125 μs, therefore, there are 8,000 frames per second on a 155.52 Mbit/s OC-3 fiber-optic circuit.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The STM-1 frame consists of overhead and pointers plus information payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The first nine columns of each frame make up the section overhead and administrative unit pointers, and the last 261 columns make up the information payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The pointers (H1, H2, H3 bytes) identify administrative units (AU) within the information payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Thus, an OC-3 circuit can carry 150.336 Mbit/s of payload, after accounting for the overhead.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Carried within the information payload, which has its own frame structure of nine rows and 261 columns, are administrative units identified by pointers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Also within the administrative unit are one or more virtual containers (VCs).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] VCs contain path overhead and VC payload.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The first column is for path overhead; it is followed by the payload container, which can itself carry other containers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Administrative units can have any phase alignment within the STM frame, and this alignment is indicated by the pointer in row four.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The section overhead (SOH) of a STM-1 signal is divided into two parts: the *regenerator section overhead* (RSOH) and the *multiplex section overhead* (MSOH).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The overheads contain information from the transmission system itself, which is used for a wide range of management functions, such as monitoring transmission quality, detecting failures, managing alarms, data communication channels, service channels, etc.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The STM frame is continuous and is transmitted in a serial fashion: byte-by-byte, row-by-row.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Called multiplex section overhead (MSOH) in SDH: 45 octets containing information about error correction and Automatic Protection Switching messages (e.g., alarms and maintenance messages) as may be required within the network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The error correction is included for STM-16 and above.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Points to the location of the J1 byte in the payload (the first byte in the virtual container).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Data transmitted from end to end is referred to as *path data*.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] 9 octets used for end-to-end signaling and error measurement.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For STS-1, the payload is referred to as the synchronous payload envelope (SPE), which in turn has 18 stuffing bytes, leading to the STS-1 payload capacity of 756 bytes.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The STS-1 payload is designed to carry a full PDH DS3 frame.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] When the DS3 enters a SONET network, path overhead is added, and that SONET network element (NE) is said to be a *path generator and terminator*.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SONET NE is *line terminating* if it processes the line overhead.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Note that wherever the line or path is terminated, the section is terminated also.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET regenerators terminate the section, but not the paths or line.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] An STS-1 payload can also be subdivided into seven *virtual tributary groups* (VTGs).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Each VTG can then be subdivided into four VT1.5 signals, each of which can carry a PDH DS1 signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] A VTG may instead be subdivided into three VT2 signals, each of which can carry a PDH E1 signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SDH equivalent of a VTG is a TUG-2; VT1.5 is equivalent to VC-11, and VT2 is equivalent to VC-12.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Three STS-1 signals may be multiplexed by time-division multiplexing to form the next level of the SONET hierarchy, the OC-3 (STS-3), running at 155.52 Mbit/s.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The signal is multiplexed by interleaving the bytes of the three STS-1 frames to form the STS-3 frame, containing 2,430 bytes and transmitted in 125 μs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Higher-speed circuits are formed by successively aggregating multiples of slower circuits, their speed always being immediately apparent from their designation.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For example, four STS-3 or AU4 signals can be aggregated to form a 622.08 Mbit/s signal designated OC-12 or STM-4.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The highest rate commonly deployed is the OC-768 or STM-256 circuit, which operates at rate of just under 38.5 Gbit/s.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Where fiber exhaustion is a concern, multiple SONET signals can be transported over multiple wavelengths on a single fiber pair by means of wavelength-division multiplexing, including dense wavelength-division multiplexing (DWDM) and coarse wavelength-division multiplexing (CWDM).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] DWDM circuits are the basis for all modern submarine communications cable systems and other long-haul circuits.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Another type of high-speed data networking circuit is 10 Gigabit Ethernet (10GbE).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The Gigabit Ethernet Alliance created two 10 Gigabit Ethernet variants: a local area variant (**LAN PHY**) with a line rate of 10.3125 Gbit/s, and a wide area variant (**WAN PHY**) with the same line rate as OC-192/STM-64 (9,953,280 kbit/s).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The WAN PHY variant encapsulates Ethernet data using a lightweight SDH/SONET frame, so as to be compatible at a low level with equipment designed to carry SDH/SONET signals, whereas the LAN PHY variant encapsulates Ethernet data using 64B/66B line coding.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] However, 10 Gigabit Ethernet does not explicitly provide any interoperability at the bitstream level with other SDH/SONET systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This differs from WDM system transponders, including both coarse and dense wavelength-division multiplexing systems (CWDM and DWDM) that currently support OC-192 SONET signals, which can normally support thin-SONET–framed 10 Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] User throughput must not deduct path overhead from the payload bandwidth, but path-overhead bandwidth is variable based on the types of cross-connects built across the optical system.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Note that the data-rate progression starts at 155 Mbit/s and increases by multiples of four.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The only exception is OC-24, which is standardized in ANSI T1.105, but not a SDH standard rate in ITU-T G.707.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Other rates, such as OC-9, OC-18, OC-36, OC-96, and OC-1536, are defined but not commonly deployed; most are considered orphaned rates.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The physical layer refers to the first layer in the OSI networking model.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The ATM and SDH layers are the regenerator section level, digital line level, transmission path level, virtual path level, and virtual channel level.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The physical layer is modeled on three major entities: transmission path, digital line and the regenerator section.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The regenerator section refers to the section and photonic layers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The photonic layer is the lowest SONET layer and it is responsible for transmitting the bits to the physical medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The section layer is responsible for generating the proper STS-N frames which are to be transmitted across the physical medium.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It deals with issues such as proper framing, error monitoring, section maintenance, and orderwire.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The line layer ensures reliable transport of the payload and overhead generated by the path layer.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It provides synchronization and multiplexing for multiple paths.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It modifies overhead bits relating to quality control.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The path layer is SONET's highest level layer.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] It takes data to be transmitted and transforms them into signals required by the line layer, and adds or modifies the path overhead bits for performance monitoring and protection switching.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Network management systems are used to configure and monitor SDH and SONET equipment either locally or remotely.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In order to allocate bandwidth throughout a network, each network element must be configured.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Although this can be done locally, through a craft interface, it is normally done through a network management system (sitting at a higher layer) that, in turn, operates through the SONET/SDH network management network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Network-element software upgrades are done mostly through the SONET/SDH management network in modern equipment.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Network elements have a very large set of standards for performance management.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The performance-management criteria allow not only monitoring the health of individual network elements, but isolating and identifying most network defects or outages.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] of network-wide performance management, so that defects and outages can be quickly identified and resolved.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] or terminal emulation program running on a laptop.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET equipment is often managed with the TL1 protocol.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] TL1 is a telecom language for managing and reconfiguring SONET network elements.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The command language used by a SONET network element, such as TL1, must be carried by other management protocols, such as SNMP, CORBA, or XML.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SDH has been mainly managed using the Q3 interface protocol suite defined in ITU recommendations Q.811 and Q.812.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] With the convergence of SONET and SDH on switching matrix and network elements architecture, newer implementations have also offered TL1.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] where the SONET network element is located.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This is for local management of that network element and, possibly, remote management of other SONET network elements.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET and SDH have dedicated data communication channels (DCCs) within the section and line overhead for management traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] To handle all of the possible management channels and signals, most modern network elements contain a router for the network commands and underlying (data) protocols.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] With advances in SONET and SDH chipsets, the traditional categories of network elements are no longer distinct.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Nevertheless, as network architectures have remained relatively constant, even newer equipment (including multi-service provisioning platforms) can be examined in light of the architectures they will support.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Thus, there is value in viewing new, as well as traditional, equipment in terms of the older categories.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Traditional regenerators terminate the section overhead, but not the line or path.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Regenerators extend long-haul routes in a way similar to most regenerators, by converting an optical signal that has already traveled a long distance into electrical format and then retransmitting a regenerated high-power signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Since the late 1990s, regenerators have been largely replaced by optical amplifiers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Also, some of the functionality of regenerators has been absorbed by the transponders of wavelength-division multiplexing systems.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] STS multiplexer and demultiplexer provide the interface between an electrical tributary network and the optical network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Add-drop multiplexers (ADMs) are the most common type of network elements.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Traditional ADMs were designed to support one of the network architectures, though new generation systems can often support several architectures, sometimes simultaneously.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] ADMs traditionally have a *high-speed side* (where the full line rate signal is supported), and a *low-speed side*, which can consist of electrical as well as optical interfaces.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The low-speed side takes in low-speed signals, which are multiplexed by the network element and sent out from the high-speed side, or vice versa.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Recent digital cross connect systems (DCSs or DXCs) support numerous high-speed signals, and allow for cross-connection of DS1s, DS3s and even STS-3s/12c and so on, from any input to any output.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Advanced DCSs can support numerous subtending rings simultaneously.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET and SDH have a limited number of architectures defined.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] These architectures allow for efficient bandwidth usage as well as protection, i.e. the ability to transmit traffic even when part of the network has failed, and are fundamental to the worldwide deployment of SONET and SDH for moving digital traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Every SDH/SONET connection on the optical physical layer uses two optical fibers, regardless of the transmission speed.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Linear Automatic Protection Switching (APS), also known as *1+1*, involves four fibers: two working fibers (one in each direction), and two protection fibers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Switching is based on the line state, and may be unidirectional (with each direction switching independently), or bidirectional (where the network elements at each end negotiate so that both directions are generally carried on the same pair of fibers).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In unidirectional path-switched rings (UPSRs), two redundant (path-level) copies of protected traffic are sent in either direction around a ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] A selector at the egress node determines which copy has the highest quality, and uses that copy, thus coping if one copy deteriorates due to a broken fiber or other failure.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] UPSRs tend to sit nearer to the edge of a network, and as such are sometimes called *collector rings*.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Because the same data is sent around the ring in both directions, the total capacity of a UPSR is equal to the line rate *N* of the OC-*N* ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For example, in an OC-3 ring with 3 STS-1s used to transport 3 DS-3s from ingress node *A* to the egress node *D*, 100 percent of the ring bandwidth (*N*=3) would be consumed by nodes *A* and *D*.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Any other nodes on the ring could only act as pass-through nodes.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SDH equivalent of UPSR is *subnetwork connection protection* (SNCP); SNCP does not impose a ring topology, but may also be used in mesh topologies.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Bidirectional line-switched ring (BLSR) comes in two varieties: two-fiber BLSR and four-fiber BLSR.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Unlike UPSR, BLSR does not send redundant copies from ingress to egress.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Rather, the ring nodes adjacent to the failure reroute the traffic "the long way" around the ring on the protection fibers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] BLSRs trade cost and complexity for bandwidth efficiency, as well as the ability to support "extra traffic" that can be pre-empted when a protection switching event occurs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In four-fiber ring, either single node failures, or multiple line failures can be supported, since a failure or maintenance action on one line causes the protection fiber connecting two nodes to be used rather than looping it around the ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] BLSRs can operate within a metropolitan region or, often, will move traffic between municipalities.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Because a BLSR does not send redundant copies from ingress to egress, the total bandwidth that a BLSR can support is not limited to the line rate *N* of the OC-*N* ring, and can actually be larger than *N* depending upon the traffic pattern on the ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In the best case, all traffic is between adjacent nodes.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The worst case is when all traffic on the ring egresses from a single node, i.e., the BLSR is serving as a collector ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In this case, the bandwidth that the ring can support is equal to the line rate *N* of the OC-*N* ring.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This is why BLSRs are seldom, if ever, deployed in collector rings, but often deployed in inter-office rings.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The SDH equivalent of BLSR is called *Multiplex Section-Shared Protection Ring* (MS-SPRING).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Clock sources used for synchronization in telecommunications networks are rated by quality, commonly called a *stratum*.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Typically, a network element uses the highest quality stratum available to it, which can be determined by monitoring the synchronization status messages (SSM) of selected clock sources.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] or a satellite-derived clock by a device in the same central office as the network element.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The interface is often a DS1, with sync-status messages supplied by the clock and placed into the DS1 overhead.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] A network element can choose (or be configured) to derive its timing from the line-level, by monitoring the S1 sync-status bytes to ensure quality.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] mode until higher-quality external timing becomes available again.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In this mode, the network element uses its own timing circuits as a reference.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] A timing loop occurs when network elements in a network are each deriving their timing from other network elements, without any of them being a "master" timing source.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This network loop will eventually see its own timing "float away" from any external networks, causing mysterious bit errors—and ultimately, in the worst cases, massive loss of traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The source of these kinds of errors can be hard to diagnose.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In general, a network that has been properly configured should never find itself in a timing loop, but some classes of silent failures could nevertheless cause this issue.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET/SDH development was originally driven by the need to transport multiple PDH signals—like DS1, E1, DS3, and E3—along with other groups of multiplexed 64 kbit/s pulse-code modulated voice traffic.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The ability to transport ATM traffic was another early application.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] In order to support large ATM bandwidths, concatenation was developed, whereby smaller multiplexing containers (e.g., STS-1) are inversely multiplexed to build up a larger container (e.g., STS-3c) to support large data-oriented pipes.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] One problem with traditional concatenation, however, is inflexibility.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Depending on the data and voice traffic mix that must be carried, there can be a large amount of unused bandwidth left over, due to the fixed sizes of concatenated containers.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] For example, fitting a 100 Mbit/s Fast Ethernet connection inside a 155 Mbit/s STS-3c container leads to considerable waste.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] More important is the need for all intermediate network elements to support newly introduced concatenation sizes.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] This problem was overcome with the introduction of Virtual Concatenation.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Virtual concatenation (VCAT) allows for a more arbitrary assembly of lower-order multiplexing containers, building larger containers of fairly arbitrary size (e.g., 100 Mbit/s) without the need for intermediate network elements to support this particular form of concatenation.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Virtual concatenation leverages the X.86 or Generic Framing Procedure (GFP) protocols in order to map payloads of arbitrary bandwidth into the virtually concatenated container.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The Link Capacity Adjustment Scheme (LCAS) allows for dynamically changing the bandwidth via dynamic virtual concatenation, multiplexing containers based on the short-term bandwidth needs in the network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] The set of next-generation SONET/SDH protocols that enable Ethernet transport is referred to as Ethernet over SONET/SDH (EoS).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] SONET/SDH was used by internet access providers for large customers, and is no longer competitive in the supply of private circuits.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] Development has stagnated for the last decade (2020) and both suppliers of equipment and operators of SONET/SDH networks are migrating to other technologies such as OTN and wide area Ethernet.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] British Telecom has recently (March 2020) closed down their KiloStream and Mega Stream products which were the last large scale uses of the BT SDH.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-digital-hierarchy] BT has also ceased new connections to their SDH network which indicates withdrawal of services soon.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The aim of Synchronous Ethernet is to provide a synchronization signal to those network resources that may eventually require such a type of signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The Synchronous Ethernet signal transmitted over the Ethernet physical layer should be traceable to an external clock, ideally a master and unique clock for the whole network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Applications include cellular networks, access technologies such as Ethernet passive optical network, and applications such as IPTV or VoIP.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Unlike time-division multiplexing networks, the Ethernet family of computer networks do not carry clock synchronization information.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Several means are defined to address this issue.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] IETF’s Network Time Protocol, IEEE's 1588-2008 Precision Time Protocol are some of them.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE architecture minimally requires replacement of the internal clock of the Ethernet card by a phase locked loop in order to feed the Ethernet PHY.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Extension of the synchronization network to consider Ethernet as a building block (ITU-T G.8261).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] This enables Synchronous Ethernet network equipment to be connected to the same synchronization network as Synchronous Digital Hierarchy (SDH).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronization for SDH can be transported over Ethernet and vice-versa.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] ITU-T G.8262 defines Synchronous Ethernet clocks compatible with SDH clocks.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronous Ethernet clocks, based on ITU-T G.813 clocks, are defined in terms of accuracy, noise transfer, holdover performance, noise tolerance and noise generation.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] These clocks are referred as Ethernet Equipment Slave clocks.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] While the IEEE 802.3 standard specifies Ethernet clocks to be within ±100 ppm.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] In addition, by timing the Ethernet clock, it is possible to achieve Primary Reference Clock (PRC) traceability at the interfaces.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] G.8262/Y.1362 is an ITU-T recommendation for Synchronous Ethernet that defines "timing characteristics of synchronous Ethernet equipment slave clock (EEC).
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] " It was first published in August 2007, amended in 2008 and 2010 and a new version published in 2010.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the Synchronization Status Message (SSM) provides traceability of synchronization signals and it is therefore required to extend the SSM functionality to Synchronous Ethernet to achieve full interoperability with SDH equipment.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the SSM message is carried in fixed locations within the SDH frame.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] However, in Ethernet there is no equivalent of a fixed frame.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The mechanisms needed to transport the SSM over Synchronous Ethernet are defined by the ITU-T in G.8264 in cooperation with IEEE.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] More specifically, the ESMC, defined by the ITU-T is based on the Organization Specific Slow Protocol (OSSP), currently specified in IEEE 802.3ay.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The ITU-T G.8264 defines a background or heart-beat message to provide a continuous indication of the clock quality level.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] However, event type messages with a new SSM quality level are generated immediately.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The ESMC protocol is composed of the standard Ethernet header for a slow protocol, an ITU-T specific header, a flag field and a type length value (TLV) structure.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The SSM encoded within the TLV is a four-bit field whose meaning is described in ITU-T G.781.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] A general requirement for SyncE was that any network element (NE) should have at least two reference clocks, and in addition, Ethernet interfaces must be able to generate their own synchronization signal in case they lose their external reference.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] If such is the case, it is said that the Ethernet node (EN) is in holdover.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronous signal must be filtered and regenerated by phase locked loop (PLL) at the Ethernet nodes since it degrades when passing through the network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronization and transport networks are partially mixed, since some NEs both transmit data and distribute clock signals to other NEs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE networks do not usually have only one topology, but rather a combination of all of them.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Duplication and security involving more than one master clock, and the existence of some kind of synchronization management protocol, are important features of modern networks.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] The aim is to minimize the problems associated with signal transport, and to avoid depending on only one clock in case of failure.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] As a result, we get an extremely precise, redundant, and solid synchronization network.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Several type of networks can be used to transport the synchronous signal and could be combined indeed.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] Some of these networks are T1/E1, SONET/SDH and any rate, and SyncE.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] However *legacy Ethernet* is not suitable for transmitting synchronization signals.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] This is important because if the signal crosses a legacy Ethernet island then the synchronization is lost.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] *Line timing*: The NE obtains its clock by deriving it from one of the input signals.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] *Through timing*: Where the Tx outputs of one interface are synchronized with the Rx inputs of the opposite interface.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] *Internal timing*: In this mode, the internal clock of the EEC is used to synchronize outputs.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] It may be a temporary holdover stage after losing the synchronization signal, or it may be a simple line configuration where no other clock is available.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] A timing loop is in bad synchronization when the clock signal has closed itself, but there is no clock, either master or slave, that would autonomously generate a non-deficient clock signal.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] This situation can be caused by a fault affecting an NE in such a way that it has been left without a reference clock, and therefore it has chosen an alternative synchronization: a signal that has turned out to be the same signal, returning by another route.
[src:sonet-sdh/synchronous-ethernet] A synchronization loop is a completely unstable situation that may provoke an immediate collapse of part of the network within the loop.
